167
00:11:36,462 --> 00:11:37,520
Nothing.

168
00:11:37,730 --> 00:11:38,856
Are you serious?

169
00:11:39,065 --> 00:11:42,626
I don't wanna talk about it
since I know you won't approve.

170
00:11:42,835 --> 00:11:43,859
Of, um?

171
00:11:44,470 --> 00:11:45,698
Nilla.
Light of Life.

172
00:11:45,905 --> 00:11:47,236
Light of what?

173
00:11:47,473 --> 00:11:49,771
[CELL PHONE CHIMING]

174
00:11:56,415 --> 00:11:57,677
Hello?
FRODE: <i>Herr Blomkvist.</i>

175
00:11:57,883 --> 00:11:59,180
Yeah.
<i>Forgive me for intruding</i>

176
00:11:59,385 --> 00:12:01,478
<i>on Christmas.</i>
<i>My name is Dirch Frode.</i>

177
00:12:01,687 --> 00:12:05,589
I'm an attorney.
I represent Henrik Vanger.
Perhaps you've heard of him?

178
00:12:05,791 --> 00:12:06,883
Yeah, of course I have.

179
00:12:07,093 --> 00:12:09,493
<i>He'd love to talk to you</i>
<i>about a private matter.</i>

180
00:12:09,695 --> 00:12:12,687
This is an awkward moment.

181
00:12:12,898 --> 00:12:15,958
<i>Oh, I'm sorry. I'm about to sit down</i>
<i>to a Christmas dinner myself.</i>

182
00:12:16,168 --> 00:12:18,193
No, that's not exactly
what I meant.

183
00:12:18,404 --> 00:12:20,736
You're referring
to your recent legal problems.

184
00:12:20,940 --> 00:12:22,771
That has provided us
with much amusement.

185
00:12:22,975 --> 00:12:23,964
I'm sorry?

186
00:12:24,176 --> 00:12:26,701
<i>Herr Vanger has little love</i>
<i>for Herr Wennerström either.</i>

187
00:12:26,912 --> 00:12:29,437
Have him call me.
But he would love to speak to you

188
00:12:29,648 --> 00:12:32,208
in person, if possible. Up north.

189
00:12:32,418 --> 00:12:34,386
<i>In Hedestad.</i>
That's not gonna be possible.

190
00:12:34,587 --> 00:12:37,385
<i>Herr Blomkvist, he's far too old</i>
<i>to go to Stockholm. Please.</i>

191
00:12:37,590 --> 00:12:39,751
Be so kind as to consider.

192
00:12:39,959 --> 00:12:42,723
<i>Hedestad is lovely in the winter.</i>

193
00:12:42,928 --> 00:12:46,921
I'll call you back on this number.
Okay?

194
00:12:57,910 --> 00:12:59,639
[SIGHS]

195
00:13:00,312 --> 00:13:02,940
Usually when I wake up
in a cold bed it's at home.

196
00:13:03,149 --> 00:13:04,878
I'm sorry.
What are you doing?

197
00:13:05,084 --> 00:13:08,053
I'm writing a press release.
Saying?

198
00:13:11,323 --> 00:13:13,723
You're taking over as publisher,
you're very sorry

199
00:13:13,926 --> 00:13:16,156
for any nuisance
Mr. Wennerström was caused,

200
00:13:16,362 --> 00:13:19,331
and I can't be reached for comment.
Are you giving up?

201
00:13:19,532 --> 00:13:20,794
Stepping aside.

202
00:13:21,200 --> 00:13:22,895
This makes me sick.

203
00:13:23,135 --> 00:13:25,103
[###]

204
00:13:46,091 --> 00:13:47,149
[SHUDDERS]

205
00:13:47,359 --> 00:13:49,327
[WOMAN SPEAKING INDISTINCTLY
OVER PA]

206
00:13:59,138 --> 00:14:01,504
FRODE: First time in Hedestad?
MIKAEL: And the last.

207
00:14:01,707 --> 00:14:04,073
FRODE:
Oh, don't say that.
It's lovely in the spring.

208
00:14:04,276 --> 00:14:06,972
You said it would be lovely
in the winter.

209
00:14:07,179 --> 00:14:09,113
Well, this is unseasonable.

210
00:14:09,315 --> 00:14:11,806
Well, I'll be on the 4:30 train
back to Stockholm.

211
00:14:12,017 --> 00:14:13,211
Unless we get snowed in.

212
00:14:14,186 --> 00:14:15,278
I'm joking.

213
00:14:15,487 --> 00:14:18,320
You'll be home tonight,
if that's what you wish.

214
00:14:19,325 --> 00:14:22,726
[###]

215
00:14:58,230 --> 00:14:59,254
VANGER:
Welcome.

216
00:14:59,531 --> 00:15:00,520
Come inside.

217
00:15:01,533 --> 00:15:03,091
It's warm.

218
00:15:03,402 --> 00:15:04,733
MIKAEL:
How do you do?

219
00:15:11,210 --> 00:15:12,677
So,

220
00:15:13,979 --> 00:15:15,378
what do you know
about me?

221
00:15:15,981 --> 00:15:19,041
You used to run one of the largest
industrial firms in the country.

222
00:15:19,251 --> 00:15:21,651
"Used to." That's correct.
Oh, I didn't mean that.

223
00:15:21,854 --> 00:15:23,583
Should I stay?
No.

224
00:15:24,189 --> 00:15:27,352
My grandfather forged the tracks

225
00:15:27,559 --> 00:15:29,686
that the 4:30 train
will take you home on.

226
00:15:30,296 --> 00:15:32,264
We stitched this country
together.

227
00:15:32,464 --> 00:15:37,163
We made the steel,
milled the lumber that
built modern Sweden.

228
00:15:37,369 --> 00:15:40,566
And what do you think
our most profitable
product now is?

229
00:15:40,773 --> 00:15:41,967
Fertilizer. Heh, heh.

230
00:15:42,207 --> 00:15:44,903
I'm not obsessed by
the declining health
of the company.

231
00:15:45,110 --> 00:15:47,704
But I am with
the settling of accounts.

232
00:15:47,913 --> 00:15:50,211
And the clock is ticking.
I need your help.

233
00:15:50,416 --> 00:15:51,781
I'm... Doing what?

234
00:15:51,984 --> 00:15:54,418
Officially, assisting
with my memoirs.

235
00:15:54,653 --> 00:15:59,147
But what you'll really be doing

236
00:15:59,358 --> 00:16:03,385
is solving a mystery
by doing what you do so well.

237
00:16:03,595 --> 00:16:05,961
Your recent legal mishap
notwithstanding.

238
00:16:06,165 --> 00:16:10,499
You will be investigating
thieves, misers, bullies,

239
00:16:10,736 --> 00:16:16,174
the most detestable collection
of people that you will ever meet.

240
00:16:16,508 --> 00:16:17,907
My family.

241
00:16:19,878 --> 00:16:21,505
[KNOCKING ON DOOR]

242
00:16:21,847 --> 00:16:24,873
[KHOMA'S "THE GUILLOTINE"
PLAYING OVER SPEAKERS]

243
00:16:25,084 --> 00:16:28,281
Would you like to sit?
I could possibly clear
a place if necessary.

244
00:16:28,487 --> 00:16:30,614
Did you make it?
Have you something for me?

245
00:16:34,193 --> 00:16:38,527
I am on welfare,
I do not administer it.
This is not enough.

246
00:16:38,731 --> 00:16:45,000
# <i>Only one thing left to do</i>
<i>I can hurt someone like you</i> #

247
00:16:45,804 --> 00:16:49,706
# <i>Tear you out</i>
<i>For all to see these lies</i> ##

248
00:16:49,908 --> 00:16:51,205
No, thank you.

249
00:16:54,380 --> 00:16:55,608
VANGER:
<i>This is Harriet.</i>

250
00:16:57,216 --> 00:17:00,014
The granddaughter
of my brother Richard.

251
00:17:00,619 --> 00:17:03,588
Richard was a Nazi
of the first order,

252
00:17:03,922 --> 00:17:09,189
joining the Nationalist Socialist
Freedom League when he was 17.

253
00:17:09,395 --> 00:17:13,957
Isn't it interesting how
fascists always steal
the word "freedom"? Heh, heh.

254
00:17:14,166 --> 00:17:15,929
[CLOCK CHIMING]

255
00:17:16,135 --> 00:17:19,832
Oh, the 4:30.
Yes, I know. Okay.

256
00:17:20,039 --> 00:17:24,840
Anyway, Richard died a martyr
to the Nazi cause in 1940.

257
00:17:25,044 --> 00:17:27,638
Missed all the real
excitement.

258
00:17:28,047 --> 00:17:32,143
But not the opportunity
to regularly beat his wife,
Margareta,

259
00:17:32,351 --> 00:17:34,046
and their son, Gottfried.

260
00:17:34,253 --> 00:17:35,948
Now, Gottfried, Harriet's father,

261
00:17:36,155 --> 00:17:38,817
was what they used to call
a good-time Charlie.

262
00:17:39,024 --> 00:17:41,618
They still call them that.
Do they? Okay.

263
00:17:41,827 --> 00:17:44,159
He was a charmer,
a ladies' man and a drunk.

264
00:17:44,363 --> 00:17:47,298
In other words, a born salesman.
Which he did for the company,

265
00:17:47,499 --> 00:17:50,161
traveling around
and taking clients out to dinner.

266
00:17:50,369 --> 00:17:52,667
Well, somebody's gotta do it.
That's right.

267
00:17:52,871 --> 00:17:55,840
Anyway, ahem,
he died in 1965.

268
00:17:56,041 --> 00:17:58,009
Drowned, drunk,
here on the island.

269
00:17:58,210 --> 00:18:02,579
His wife, Isabella, who had
been pretty much useless
as a parent before,

270
00:18:02,781 --> 00:18:05,147
became even more so
after his death,

271
00:18:05,350 --> 00:18:07,944
which is when I began
looking after the children.

272
00:18:08,187 --> 00:18:11,156
Martin, who runs Vanger Industries,
now that I'm retired.

273
00:18:11,356 --> 00:18:12,914
That's right, I Googled him.

274
00:18:13,125 --> 00:18:14,251
VANGER:
And Harriet.

275
00:18:15,427 --> 00:18:19,420
Ah. She was bright, curious,

276
00:18:19,998 --> 00:18:22,899
a winning combination
in any person.

277
00:18:23,502 --> 00:18:26,494
And beautiful.
Yeah.

278
00:18:27,906 --> 00:18:29,703
Something happened to her?

279
00:18:29,908 --> 00:18:32,069
Someone in the family
murdered Harriet,

280
00:18:32,811 --> 00:18:34,745
and for the past 40 years,

281
00:18:34,947 --> 00:18:37,211
has been trying
to drive me insane.

282
00:18:37,416 --> 00:18:39,213
[###]

283
00:18:39,418 --> 00:18:42,444
VANGER:
<i>It was September 24th, 1966.</i>

284
00:18:42,654 --> 00:18:44,417
A Saturday.

285
00:18:44,623 --> 00:18:46,284
Harriet was 16.

286
00:18:46,558 --> 00:18:47,582
My brothers

287
00:18:47,793 --> 00:18:51,889
<i>and their wives and their</i>
<i>children and grandchildren</i>
<i>were all gathered here</i>

288
00:18:52,097 --> 00:18:55,089
<i>for our loathsome annual</i>
<i>board meeting and dinner.</i>

289
00:18:55,300 --> 00:18:59,293
<i>It was also the day the yacht club</i>
<i>held their autumn parade.</i>

290
00:18:59,505 --> 00:19:02,633
<i>Harriet, with one or two school</i>
<i>friends, went into town to see it.</i>

291
00:19:02,841 --> 00:19:05,901
She returned a little after 2:00.

292
00:19:06,111 --> 00:19:09,945
<i>She came into the parlor.</i>
<i>She asked if she could talk to me.</i>

293
00:19:10,149 --> 00:19:12,379
I honestly don't remember
what I was doing

294
00:19:12,584 --> 00:19:14,415
that I thought
was more important,

295
00:19:14,620 --> 00:19:17,020
<i>but I told her</i>
<i>to give me a few minutes.</i>

296
00:19:18,790 --> 00:19:23,591
It was during those few minutes
that something else occurred.

297
00:19:26,398 --> 00:19:29,799
<i>The accident had nothing to do</i>
<i>with Harriet,</i>

298
00:19:30,002 --> 00:19:31,094
and yet everything.

299
00:19:32,137 --> 00:19:35,300
<i>Heh. It was chaos as everybody</i>
<i>put down what they were doing.</i>

300
00:19:35,507 --> 00:19:37,805
<i>Police, ambulance, fire brigade,</i>

301
00:19:38,010 --> 00:19:41,878
<i>reporters, photographers, onlookers</i>
<i>all quickly arrived from town</i>

302
00:19:42,080 --> 00:19:46,540
<i>just as we on the island, the family,</i>
<i>hurried to the bridge from our side.</i>

303
00:19:46,785 --> 00:19:48,150
<i>The driver of the car,</i>

304
00:19:48,353 --> 00:19:49,911
a man named Aronsson,

305
00:19:50,122 --> 00:19:52,386
<i>was pinned and severely injured.</i>

306
00:19:52,591 --> 00:19:55,492
<i>We tried desperately</i>
<i>to pry him loose with our hands</i>

307
00:19:55,694 --> 00:19:58,026
<i>since metal tools might spark.</i>

308
00:19:58,230 --> 00:19:59,219
[INDISTINCT SHOUTING]

309
00:19:59,431 --> 00:20:03,162
<i>It was an hour after the crash</i>
<i>that Harriet was in the kitchen.</i>

310
00:20:03,368 --> 00:20:05,461
Anna herself saw her.

311
00:20:09,608 --> 00:20:14,477
<i>Well, we finally got poor Aronsson</i>
<i>out of his car and off to the hospital.</i>

312
00:20:15,047 --> 00:20:18,175
<i>Just as we from our side</i>

313
00:20:18,383 --> 00:20:21,352
<i>slowly drifted back to the house.</i>

314
00:20:23,355 --> 00:20:25,550
<i>The sun was down,</i>
<i>the excitement over.</i>

315
00:20:25,958 --> 00:20:28,051
<i>We sat down to dinner.</i>

316
00:20:28,260 --> 00:20:29,852
<i>It was then that I noticed</i>

317
00:20:30,395 --> 00:20:31,828
<i>Harriet wasn't there.</i>

318
00:20:33,065 --> 00:20:34,999
<i>And she wasn't there</i>
<i>the next morning.</i>

319
00:20:35,934 --> 00:20:36,923
<i>Or the next.</i>

320
00:20:37,736 --> 00:20:39,067
Or the next 40 years.

321
00:20:42,841 --> 00:20:44,536
<i>What was she going to tell me?</i>

322
00:20:44,743 --> 00:20:47,940
Why didn't I make time for her?
Why didn't I listen?

323
00:20:48,146 --> 00:20:51,513
And she couldn't have just run away?
No. Not without being seen.

324
00:20:51,717 --> 00:20:53,344
The firemen stayed out all night

325
00:20:53,552 --> 00:20:55,452
<i>on the bridge</i>
<i>pumping up gasoline.</i>

326
00:20:55,654 --> 00:20:58,452
<i>No one swam across</i>
<i>or took a boat.</i>

327
00:20:58,657 --> 00:21:01,353
All the boats were still tied up
on this side Sunday.

328
00:21:01,560 --> 00:21:04,120
Believe me, I checked.

329
00:21:06,231 --> 00:21:08,096
MIKAEL:
She couldn't have just fallen
and drowned?

330
00:21:08,300 --> 00:21:13,033
No. The currents aren't
strong here. Anything that
falls in the water turns up.

331
00:21:13,238 --> 00:21:14,466
Like her father.

332
00:21:14,673 --> 00:21:17,039
His body didn't drift
more than 10 meters

333
00:21:17,242 --> 00:21:19,608
when he drowned the year before.

334
00:21:19,811 --> 00:21:22,905
Oh, no. Someone killed her.

335
00:21:23,115 --> 00:21:25,709
Someone on the island
that day.

336
00:21:25,917 --> 00:21:27,885
Someone close enough to know

337
00:21:28,086 --> 00:21:32,455
what she used to give me
each year on my birthday.

338
00:21:34,459 --> 00:21:36,552
Those are from her.

339
00:21:37,095 --> 00:21:40,531
And the rest, from her killer.

340
00:21:53,445 --> 00:21:54,673
Who knows about these?

341
00:21:54,913 --> 00:21:58,349
There's me, the police,
the killer,

342
00:21:58,784 --> 00:21:59,773
and now you.

343
00:22:08,827 --> 00:22:11,261
VANGER:
<i>After the police investigation</i>
<i>evaporated,</i>

344
00:22:11,463 --> 00:22:14,227
<i>I kept at it, studying</i>
<i>all the information there was.</i>

345
00:22:14,733 --> 00:22:18,601
I have spent half my life
examining the events
of a single day.

346
00:22:18,804 --> 00:22:20,931
I understand your frustration,

347
00:22:21,139 --> 00:22:23,937
but what you're asking me to do,
it's a waste of money.

348
00:22:24,142 --> 00:22:27,236
But we haven't discussed your fee.
We don't need to.

349
00:22:27,446 --> 00:22:28,845
Thank you.

350
00:22:29,047 --> 00:22:32,642
I can't find something
you've been unable
to find in 40 years.

351
00:22:32,851 --> 00:22:36,651
You don't know that.
You have a very keen
investigative mind.

352
00:22:37,356 --> 00:22:38,721
Here's what I propose:

353
00:22:38,957 --> 00:22:40,652
You come stay
on the island.

354
00:22:40,859 --> 00:22:44,022
I have a nice little cottage
by the water you can use.

355
00:22:44,229 --> 00:22:46,129
You study the material
I send you.

356
00:22:46,331 --> 00:22:48,526
You find something I've missed
or you don't.

357
00:22:48,734 --> 00:22:51,794
What you're asking me to do
is set aside my life and career for...

358
00:22:52,003 --> 00:22:53,994
Think of this
as a well-deserved holiday.

359
00:22:54,206 --> 00:22:58,700
A way of avoiding
all those people that you
might want to avoid right now.

360
00:22:58,910 --> 00:23:01,401
As for compensation,
I'll pay you double your salary

361
00:23:01,613 --> 00:23:03,308
for as many months as it takes.

362
00:23:03,515 --> 00:23:06,245
Quadruple it if you solve the mystery.
Herr Vanger...

363
00:23:06,485 --> 00:23:08,578
I'm not done.
I will throw in one more thing,

364
00:23:08,787 --> 00:23:10,948
even though
you're a terrible negotiator.

365
00:23:11,156 --> 00:23:13,681
It's something you want
more than anything else,

366
00:23:13,892 --> 00:23:17,328
and it can't be bought at any price.
So let me give it to you.

367
00:23:18,063 --> 00:23:20,896
Hans-Erik Wennerström.

368
00:23:21,867 --> 00:23:24,097
He began his career
working for me,

369
00:23:24,302 --> 00:23:27,965
and I have followed it with interest,
shall we say, ever since.

370
00:23:28,173 --> 00:23:30,141
[###]

371
00:23:31,009 --> 00:23:32,374
You were right about him.

372
00:23:33,278 --> 00:23:35,371
You just couldn't prove it.

373
00:23:41,586 --> 00:23:42,780
[DEVICE BEEPS]

374
00:24:05,977 --> 00:24:09,378
We're in the middle
of the worst crisis ever,
and you're writing a memoir.

375
00:24:09,581 --> 00:24:13,210
You fired me. I need something to do.
You fired you.

376
00:24:15,353 --> 00:24:17,412
I need you here, not the North Pole.

377
00:24:17,622 --> 00:24:19,988
Mikael, you know
what this is going to look like.

378
00:24:20,192 --> 00:24:22,251
Like I've been gutted.
I'm running away. I am.

379
00:24:22,461 --> 00:24:25,294
Wennerström wants to see me
wave a white flag, not a red flag.

380
00:24:25,497 --> 00:24:28,625
If it looks like there's a problem
between us, it'll satisfy him.

381
00:24:28,834 --> 00:24:30,199
There is a problem between us.

382
00:24:30,402 --> 00:24:32,927
He won't be satisfied
until he shuts us down.

383
00:24:33,605 --> 00:24:37,473
You're leaving me to fight him alone.
It's four hours by train.

384
00:24:42,781 --> 00:24:44,942
It's not the North Pole.

