00:30:22,120 --> 00:30:25,283
Cecilia's brother, Birger,
lives over there.

458
00:30:25,490 --> 00:30:27,082
MIKAEL:
Who doesn't he speak to?

459
00:30:27,292 --> 00:30:28,384
VANGER:
You, probably.

460
00:30:28,593 --> 00:30:32,051
But you wouldn't want him to.
He can be just as unpleasant
as Harald.

461
00:30:32,263 --> 00:30:33,992
Quickly losing track
of who's who here.

462
00:30:34,199 --> 00:30:37,168
Ho-ho-ho. How you'll wish
it were always so.

463
00:30:37,368 --> 00:30:41,304
Soon you will know us all
only too well, with my apologies.

464
00:30:41,573 --> 00:30:46,636
Now, out there, my grandnephew
Martin's house, Harriet's brother.

465
00:30:46,845 --> 00:30:48,176
Who speaks to him?

466
00:30:48,379 --> 00:30:51,712
I speak to him.
He runs the company now,
as I think I told you.

467
00:30:51,916 --> 00:30:53,247
[GUNSHOT]

468
00:30:53,985 --> 00:30:57,614
Oh. Someone's shooting
his dinner. Gunnar, probably.

469
00:30:57,822 --> 00:30:59,119
Oh, yes, I met him earlier.

470
00:30:59,324 --> 00:31:02,851
He was 19 when
Harriet disappeared.

471
00:31:03,528 --> 00:31:05,189
Well, he lives over there.

472
00:31:07,332 --> 00:31:08,856
And you live there.
Sorry?

473
00:31:09,067 --> 00:31:10,591
Your house.

474
00:31:12,203 --> 00:31:15,001
Oh. Ha. Oh, yes.

475
00:31:15,573 --> 00:31:17,268
Yes, you're right.

476
00:31:17,475 --> 00:31:19,102
The man who hires the detective

477
00:31:19,310 --> 00:31:22,541
should always be kept
on the suspects list.

478
00:31:42,533 --> 00:31:43,557
[SIGHS]

479
00:31:43,768 --> 00:31:45,736
[###]

480
00:31:57,115 --> 00:31:59,242
[INDISTINCT SHOUTING]

481
00:32:11,696 --> 00:32:14,164
[INAUDIBLE DIALOGUE]

482
00:32:15,166 --> 00:32:16,793
Her mother.

483
00:32:44,462 --> 00:32:45,486
[SPEAKING INDISTINCTLY]

484
00:32:45,697 --> 00:32:47,961
VANGER:
But what about the search? Please.

485
00:32:49,167 --> 00:32:52,034
Please. I beg you.

486
00:33:12,924 --> 00:33:14,619
[SHOUTS INDISTINCTLY]

487
00:33:23,334 --> 00:33:26,792
MORELL:
<i>The fact that I never found</i>
<i>a body was not surprising.</i>

488
00:33:27,005 --> 00:33:29,906
<i>You can't dig up an entire island.</i>

489
00:33:31,175 --> 00:33:33,336
But neither could I find the motive.

490
00:33:33,544 --> 00:33:36,172
Was it spontaneous?
Was it calculated?

491
00:33:36,381 --> 00:33:38,713
Did she know something
someone wished she didn't?

492
00:33:38,916 --> 00:33:42,443
Was it about business?
Business? Well, she was 16.

493
00:33:42,653 --> 00:33:44,348
And very bright.

494
00:33:44,555 --> 00:33:47,251
Henrik told me and many others
he could easily see her

495
00:33:47,458 --> 00:33:49,085
running the company one day.

496
00:33:49,694 --> 00:33:52,322
She was with some friends
that day at a parade.

497
00:33:52,530 --> 00:33:56,193
She told them she was
feeling unwell. She left early.

498
00:33:56,401 --> 00:33:59,859
But they also told me
she kept secrets from them too.

499
00:34:00,238 --> 00:34:03,639
The main thing I learned was that
teenage girls are complicated.

500
00:34:03,841 --> 00:34:06,105
I have one.
Oh, then you know.

501
00:34:06,411 --> 00:34:09,471
I wanted to, uh, ahem,

502
00:34:09,680 --> 00:34:11,409
ask you about this.

503
00:34:14,185 --> 00:34:16,710
She received that from Henrik
the Christmas before.

504
00:34:19,223 --> 00:34:22,158
I've studied it more times
than I can say.

505
00:34:23,561 --> 00:34:24,892
I know every page of it.

506
00:34:25,096 --> 00:34:27,394
It's the last page I was curious about.
As was I.

507
00:34:27,598 --> 00:34:31,500
It's a list of names, numbers
and it must have some significance.

508
00:34:31,702 --> 00:34:33,135
All local phone numbers.

509
00:34:33,337 --> 00:34:35,567
The first belonged
to a woman, Margot,

510
00:34:35,773 --> 00:34:38,674
whose mother was Magda,
who denied knowing Harriet.

511
00:34:38,876 --> 00:34:41,868
The fourth, R.L.,
belonged to Rosmarie Larsson,

512
00:34:42,080 --> 00:34:45,914
an elderly woman who died
some years before.

513
00:34:46,117 --> 00:34:50,486
The other three were not connected
in any way that I could find.

514
00:34:51,122 --> 00:34:54,319
I reminded you of things
you'd rather forget, and I'm sorry.

515
00:34:54,559 --> 00:34:56,527
I can't forget.

516
00:34:57,929 --> 00:34:59,658
It's my Rebecka case.

517
00:35:00,498 --> 00:35:01,897
Uh, I don't know what that is.

518
00:35:02,600 --> 00:35:07,264
Every policeman has at least one
unsolved case to obsess over.

519
00:35:08,072 --> 00:35:10,472
Back then we had
an Officer Torstensson.

520
00:35:10,708 --> 00:35:13,541
Year after year, he kept
going back to this Rebecka case.

521
00:35:13,744 --> 00:35:16,941
Taking out the files,
studying them over and over.

522
00:35:17,148 --> 00:35:19,173
We were young.
We laughed at him.

523
00:35:19,383 --> 00:35:21,283
And that was also
a missing-girl case?

524
00:35:21,486 --> 00:35:24,216
No, no, no,
that's not why I mention it.

525
00:35:24,422 --> 00:35:27,289
I'm talking about
the soul of a policeman.

526
00:35:27,859 --> 00:35:30,726
MORELL:
<i>Poor old Torstensson</i>
<i>never solved it.</i>

527
00:35:30,928 --> 00:35:33,260
<i>And he never let it go.</i>

528
00:35:34,432 --> 00:35:36,957
[TRAIN HORN BLARING]

529
00:35:40,438 --> 00:35:42,338
MAN:
So how's Mr. Palmgren doing?

530
00:35:42,907 --> 00:35:45,671
I heard he had a stroke
of some kind? Huh?

531
00:35:45,877 --> 00:35:46,901
It's terrible.

532
00:35:48,246 --> 00:35:51,113
Now, what exactly do you do
at this security company?

533
00:35:51,315 --> 00:35:53,044
Make coffee, sort mail.

534
00:35:53,251 --> 00:35:54,878
But not full-time.

535
00:35:55,453 --> 00:35:57,080
Not even part-time consistently.

536
00:35:57,288 --> 00:36:02,225
They somehow got along without
coffee or mail in July and August?

537
00:36:06,931 --> 00:36:09,058
How much do you make there?
Enough.

538
00:36:10,835 --> 00:36:11,893
How much is your rent?

539
00:36:12,103 --> 00:36:13,570
I pay my rent.

540
00:36:17,241 --> 00:36:19,038
And when was the last time
you were late?

541
00:36:19,243 --> 00:36:20,232
Never.

542
00:36:21,546 --> 00:36:24,982
You think that thing through your
eyebrow makes you attractive?

543
00:36:27,351 --> 00:36:28,409
Here's the problem.

544
00:36:30,154 --> 00:36:33,055
There's a discrepancy
between the obligation

545
00:36:33,257 --> 00:36:37,353
of Mr. Palmgren's guardianship and
the management of your finances.

546
00:36:37,562 --> 00:36:40,759
There's no discrepancy. It was clear
I could manage my own finances.

547
00:36:40,965 --> 00:36:42,057
That is not clear to me.

548
00:36:42,266 --> 00:36:44,427
I'm not a child.
You are not. But you were.

549
00:36:44,635 --> 00:36:46,728
And between then and now,
you were committed

550
00:36:46,938 --> 00:36:49,736
to the locked ward of St. Stefan's
where you continued

551
00:36:49,941 --> 00:36:52,034
to display violent aggression.

552
00:36:52,777 --> 00:36:55,439
And you failed to adapt
to four foster homes,

553
00:36:55,646 --> 00:36:58,911
arrested twice for intoxication,
twice for narcotics,

554
00:36:59,116 --> 00:37:03,143
again for assault,
smashing a bottle into a man's face.

555
00:37:03,354 --> 00:37:05,618
And it's not even that long ago.

556
00:37:05,823 --> 00:37:10,089
You may have conned
Mr. Palmgren into thinking
that you have changed,

557
00:37:10,294 --> 00:37:12,091
but when I'm looking at this,

558
00:37:12,296 --> 00:37:16,232
not to mention the way
you're looking at me now,

559
00:37:16,434 --> 00:37:18,197
I don't think you have.

560
00:37:18,703 --> 00:37:21,331
So the good old
Mr. Palmgren days are over.

561
00:37:21,539 --> 00:37:24,508
Starting now, you will be given
a monthly allowance.

562
00:37:24,709 --> 00:37:26,939
You'll provide me with receipts
for your expenses.

563
00:37:27,144 --> 00:37:30,341
If the numbers don't balance,
I assume the difference
is going to drugs.

564
00:37:30,548 --> 00:37:32,379
I've taken care of myself
since I was 10.

565
00:37:32,583 --> 00:37:34,016
The state has taken care of you.

566
00:37:34,218 --> 00:37:36,880
Miss Salander, please,
look at me, this is important.

567
00:37:37,088 --> 00:37:40,387
Since your behavior
is elaborately documented in here,

568
00:37:40,625 --> 00:37:43,116
it will shock no one
if I chose an alternative

569
00:37:43,327 --> 00:37:46,694
to the very lenient arrangement
I have just outlined.

570
00:37:49,200 --> 00:37:53,296
Would you prefer
institutionalization?

571
00:37:55,873 --> 00:37:58,171
[###]

572
00:38:07,451 --> 00:38:08,440
[SCREAMS]

573
00:38:14,292 --> 00:38:15,350
Mikael?
MIKAEL: Yes.

574
00:38:15,559 --> 00:38:17,083
I'm Liv.
Oh, hi.

575
00:38:17,295 --> 00:38:18,887
We're going to the same place.
Hop in.

576
00:38:19,096 --> 00:38:20,427
Oh, good, thank you.

577
00:38:28,773 --> 00:38:31,901
I found him at death's door,
halfway up the hill.

578
00:38:32,176 --> 00:38:35,009
I'm afraid I'm a little out of shape.
It's a climb for anyone.

579
00:38:35,212 --> 00:38:37,612
I should've warned you. Come in.
MIKAEL: Thank you, Martin.

580
00:38:37,815 --> 00:38:39,339
MARTIN:
Henrik says great things about you.

581
00:38:39,550 --> 00:38:43,953
LIV: Mmm. Martin? Smells wonderful.
MARTIN: No. Leave your shoes on.

582
00:38:44,155 --> 00:38:45,349
LIV:
What are we drinking?

583
00:38:45,556 --> 00:38:47,217
MIKAEL:
What a place. Look at that view.

584
00:38:47,425 --> 00:38:50,861
I used to work in
the company's petrochemical
division in Göteborg.

585
00:38:51,062 --> 00:38:52,586
When it was sold,
I went with it.

586
00:38:52,797 --> 00:38:54,059
A dark day.

587
00:38:54,432 --> 00:38:57,629
LIV:
I live in Hong Kong, but come back
to Stockholm for family events.

588
00:38:57,835 --> 00:39:00,235
And I drive up to spend
a couple of days with Martin.

589
00:39:00,438 --> 00:39:03,805
It's just the moose steak she wants.
Who can blame her? It's wonderful.

590
00:39:04,008 --> 00:39:05,999
[WIND WHISTLING]

591
00:39:06,210 --> 00:39:09,111
Something's left open.
Do you like this wine,

592
00:39:09,313 --> 00:39:13,079
or you want to try something else?
No, no, it's fine.

593
00:39:13,284 --> 00:39:16,253
[TAKEN B Y TREES' "ANNANASS"
PLAYING OVER SPEAKERS]

594
00:39:17,521 --> 00:39:19,546
You're writing a book now,
Martin said.

595
00:39:19,757 --> 00:39:22,351
Henrik's biography.
I love Henrik. He's fascinating.

596
00:39:22,560 --> 00:39:23,822
Martin too.

597
00:39:24,028 --> 00:39:27,191
Together they are
the old Sweden and the new.

598
00:39:27,398 --> 00:39:28,626
Yes, they are.

599
00:39:30,468 --> 00:39:32,766
You know about Harriet,
right?

600
00:39:33,671 --> 00:39:35,468
You don't?
Yes, I do.

601
00:39:36,607 --> 00:39:40,441
The family doesn't want
to talk about it, but it can't
be swept under the rug.

602
00:39:40,644 --> 00:39:42,509
What can't?
Harriet.

603
00:39:42,880 --> 00:39:44,108
We can talk about it later.

604
00:39:44,315 --> 00:39:47,079
Uh... We can talk about it now.

605
00:39:47,451 --> 00:39:49,510
Liv knows everything
about my crazy family.

606
00:39:49,720 --> 00:39:52,154
That's why she'll never marry me.
That's one reason.

607
00:39:52,356 --> 00:39:54,324
MARTIN:
I don't want to read
about that in the book.

608
00:39:54,525 --> 00:39:56,755
Everything else is fine.
Harriet certainly.

609
00:39:57,261 --> 00:40:00,822
You know,
everything changed after that.

610
00:40:01,031 --> 00:40:03,329
Not just the family,
but the company as well.

611
00:40:03,534 --> 00:40:05,559
How so?
We're not Ericsson or Nordea.

612
00:40:05,770 --> 00:40:09,228
But we're still the largest
family-owned company
in the country.

613
00:40:09,540 --> 00:40:11,633
At our height we had
40,000 employees.

614
00:40:11,842 --> 00:40:13,036
We have half of that now.

615
00:40:13,244 --> 00:40:17,112
And that downward slide
began after my sister's death.

616
00:40:17,314 --> 00:40:19,282
[###]

617
00:40:20,885 --> 00:40:23,979
It broke Henrik's
entrepreneurial spirit

618
00:40:24,388 --> 00:40:25,377
and his heart.

619
00:40:26,323 --> 00:40:28,985
Uh... You were here that day?
MARTIN: I came in later,

620
00:40:29,193 --> 00:40:31,889
after the accident on the bridge,
with the 4:30 train.

621
00:40:32,096 --> 00:40:35,031
I know it well.
A terrible day.

622
00:40:35,900 --> 00:40:36,889
[SIGHS]

623
00:40:37,101 --> 00:40:38,762
And the days after, you know?

624
00:40:38,969 --> 00:40:43,201
Searching, not finding.
Even worse.

625
00:40:44,108 --> 00:40:48,010
This event, Mikael, it has to have
a big part in your book.

626
00:40:50,214 --> 00:40:51,511
[MARTIN SPEAKS IN SWEDISH]

627
00:41:10,768 --> 00:41:13,293
I got a call from
social welfare.

628
00:41:14,104 --> 00:41:16,299
I've been assigned
a new guardian.

629
00:41:19,710 --> 00:41:21,678
[###]

630
00:42:19,436 --> 00:42:20,733
Hi.
Hello.

631
00:42:20,938 --> 00:42:23,372
I thought I'd come over
and say hello.

632
00:42:23,574 --> 00:42:27,066
I'm Cecilia.
Oh, yes. Please, come in.

633
00:42:30,414 --> 00:42:32,405
Can I get you some coffee?

634
00:42:32,616 --> 00:42:34,880
No, thank you.

635
00:42:44,295 --> 00:42:48,857
We are all uncomfortable
with the idea of a chronicle
of our family.

636
00:42:49,066 --> 00:42:51,830
It's not about the family.
It's about Henrik and the company.

637
00:42:52,169 --> 00:42:53,193
Like I said.

638
00:42:54,772 --> 00:42:57,798
It's not my intention to present
a malicious portrait of anyone.

639
00:42:58,008 --> 00:42:59,566
CECILIA:
Unlike the one that
landed you in court.

640
00:42:59,777 --> 00:43:02,940
Unlike that one, yes.

641
00:43:03,314 --> 00:43:06,477
So you're not really here to find out
what happened to Harriet.

642
00:43:06,684 --> 00:43:10,450
I can't ignore such a dramatic event,
but, no, that's by no means my focus.

643
00:43:10,654 --> 00:43:12,588
Those boxes that Gunnar
carted down here,

644
00:43:12,790 --> 00:43:17,124
which are where, in the closet now?
Those weren't Henrik's investigation?

645
00:43:17,528 --> 00:43:22,864
I wonder sometimes who's crazier,
my Nazi father or my obsessed uncle.

646
00:43:23,067 --> 00:43:24,659
Since we're talking about her,

647
00:43:24,868 --> 00:43:26,961
since you brought her up,
what was she like?

648
00:43:27,171 --> 00:43:28,297
What was Harriet like?

649
00:43:28,505 --> 00:43:31,133
I'm sure Henrik has told you.
He was my age back then.

650
00:43:31,342 --> 00:43:34,505
He couldn't know what was
really going on with a teenager.

651
00:43:34,712 --> 00:43:35,838
You were the same age.

652
00:43:36,046 --> 00:43:37,911
My sister Anita
was closer to her in age.

653
00:43:38,115 --> 00:43:40,845
She knew Harriet better than anyone.
You should talk to her.

654
00:43:41,051 --> 00:43:43,645
I'd love to. Where is she?
If I had to guess, London.

655
00:43:44,388 --> 00:43:46,151
You don't know
where your sister lives?

656
00:43:46,357 --> 00:43:49,520
I haven't seen her in years.
We never really got along.

657
00:43:49,727 --> 00:43:53,163
I'm getting used to that comment.
She hates this place more than I do.

658
00:43:53,364 --> 00:43:56,197
She left.
Moved to London, that was it.

659
00:43:56,500 --> 00:43:59,401
You couldn't pay her to send
a Christmas card, much less visit.

660
00:43:59,603 --> 00:44:01,332
I'll track her down for you.

661
00:44:01,538 --> 00:44:04,701
If you do, and try talking
to her about us,

662
00:44:04,908 --> 00:44:08,036
don't be surprised
if she tells you to fuck off.

663
00:44:10,547 --> 00:44:13,345
[DOOR OPENS THEN CLOSES]

664
00:44:14,752 --> 00:44:16,242
MAN:
You're backed up, aren't you?

665
00:44:16,453 --> 00:44:18,318
[CLAN OF XYMO X'S
"IN YOUR ARMS AGAIN"
PLAYING OVER SPEAKERS]

666
00:44:18,522 --> 00:44:19,682
Hard drive at home, yeah.

667
00:44:19,890 --> 00:44:22,688
Okay. That's good,
because this one's done.

668
00:44:27,965 --> 00:44:30,798
BJURMAN:
<i>Have you ever had any</i>
<i>sexually transmitted diseases?</i>

669
00:44:31,035 --> 00:44:33,401
[BUFFER WHIRRING]

670
00:44:34,571 --> 00:44:38,337
<i>And when was the last time</i>
<i>that you were tested for HIV?</i>

671
00:44:40,644 --> 00:44:42,908
<i>How many partners have you had</i>
<i>in the last month?</i>

672
00:44:44,415 --> 00:44:46,747
And how many of those were men?

673
00:44:50,254 --> 00:44:53,280
It's regulation, I have to ask
these things. It's a health matter.

674
00:44:53,490 --> 00:44:54,582
Write what you want.

675
00:44:54,792 --> 00:44:57,124
And why do you need
such an expensive computer?

676
00:44:57,327 --> 00:44:59,557
For work.
Making coffee, sorting mail.

677
00:44:59,763 --> 00:45:02,698
I should have control of my money.
And you will.

678
00:45:02,900 --> 00:45:05,596
Once you learn to be sociable,
get along with people. Huh?

679
00:45:05,803 --> 00:45:07,532
Can you do that?

680
00:45:10,007 --> 00:45:14,171
Why don't we start
with that now, huh?

681
00:45:16,180 --> 00:45:19,877
Why don't we start with me?

682
00:45:26,590 --> 00:45:29,559
You do something for me,
I do something for you.

683
00:45:30,894 --> 00:45:32,759
That's what normal people do.

684
00:45:33,797 --> 00:45:35,765
[###]

685
00:45:47,644 --> 00:45:49,976
I want you to have that computer.

686
00:46:06,930 --> 00:46:08,261
Feel that.

687
00:46:09,233 --> 00:46:10,825
That's gabardine.

688
00:46:15,172 --> 00:46:17,106
[BELT CLINKING]

689
00:46:17,307 --> 00:46:19,002
Unzip it.

690
00:46:25,916 --> 00:46:27,144
[UNZIPS]

691
00:46:27,751 --> 00:46:29,412
And...

692
00:46:30,954 --> 00:46:32,581
And...

693
00:46:38,395 --> 00:46:39,828
[GASPS]

694
00:46:46,203 --> 00:46:48,137
I like the reticence.

695
00:46:49,907 --> 00:46:51,374
It's almost convincing.

696
